    "Background": {
      "text": "White shark (\nCarcharodon carcharias\n), tiger shark (\nGaleocerdo curvier\n) appear to be disposed to human attacks than other species\nApproximately 70-100 shark attacks worldwide per year and 5-15 deaths",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Direct traumatic effects depend on size and species of shark\nTypically, attack appendages of victims\nIn 70% on surface swimmers, only the lower limb is involved\nUpper limb may be injured when the victim attempts to fight off the attack\nMassive tissue injury\nSubstantial tissue loss from stripping mechanism and extremity amputation are common\nHemorrhagic shock\nExtremely high incidence of contamination with atypical microorganisms leading to\nsoft tissue infections\nand necrosis\nMost common organisms include\nVibrio\nspp.\nOther potential organisms include\nPseudomonas\n,\nStaph\n,\nCitrobacter\n,\nMicrococcus\nDeath is usually due to lack of prehospital resuscitation, hemorrhagic shock, or drowning",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
